{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17613642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17613642"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:37:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:37:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16320"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16320","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16320"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.57,0.05,0.14,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9011"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116145"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9011","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9011"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16320"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98141"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7515"},{"type":"tags","id":"8403"},{"type":"tags","id":"8547"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21442"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21446"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116145"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe eyelid is composed of multiple tissue layers, each with distinct properties and functions. One layer is particularly susceptible to fluid accumulation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following layers of the eyelid is the primary site for fluid or blood accumulation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tarsal plate","Palpebral conjunctiva","Eyelid skin","Loose connective tissue","Orbicularis oculi muscle"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eloose connective tissue\u003C/strong\u003E layer of the eyelid, located between the skin and orbicularis oculi muscle, is the primary site for fluid and blood accumulation. Its loose arrangement and rich vascular supply make it particularly susceptible to oedema and haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other layers are less likely sites for fluid accumulation. The \u003Cstrong\u003Etarsal plate\u003C/strong\u003E is dense fibrous connective tissue that provides structural support and is too rigid for significant fluid accumulation. The \u003Cstrong\u003Epalpebral conjunctiva\u003C/strong\u003E is a thin mucous membrane that lines the inner surface of the eyelid. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eeyelid skin\u003C/strong\u003E is the thinnest skin in the body but is too dense for significant fluid accumulation. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eorbicularis oculi muscle\u003C/strong\u003E is striated muscle tissue that closes the eyelid and is too dense for significant fluid accumulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the layered structure of the eyelid is important for recognising common clinical presentations such as periorbital oedema and haematoma formation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The eyelid consists of five distinct layers from anterior to posterior: skin, loose connective tissue, orbicularis oculi muscle, tarsal plate, and conjunctiva.","The loose connective tissue layer of the eyelid readily accumulates fluid or blood due to its loose arrangement and abundant vascular supply."],"references":["Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Probst, L., \u0026 Tsai, J. (2024). Ophthalmology: Clinical and Surgical Principles. CRC Press","Salmon, J. F. (2024). Kanski\u0027s Clinical Ophthalmology E-Book: A Systematic Approach. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kels BD, Grzybowski A, Grant-Kels JM. Human ocular anatomy. Clin Dermatol. 2015 Mar-Apr;33(2):140-6. doi: 10.1016/j.clindermatol.2014.10.006. PMID: 25704934"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98141"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16320"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98141"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-27T18:10:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-27T18:10:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9011"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116145"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","